Abstract: This document describes requirements for implementing the [Network of Terms API](https://docs.nde.nl/services/network-of-terms/graphql) in collection management systems. By following these requirements, implementers enable users to efficiently search for and link to terms from terminology sources.
</pre>


Introduction {#introduction}
============

*This section is non-normative.*

The [[NDE-CMS#implementation-of-the-nde-network-of-terms|Requirements for Collection Management Systems]] include 
a general obligation for vendors to implement the Network of Terms API in their collection management systems. 
However, feedback from users of these systems, as well as questions from vendors, has shown the need for more detailed guidance.
The requirements below provide such guidance, specifying in more detail the steps needed for performant 
and user-friendly implementations of the Network of Terms. The goal is to help both users and vendors.

Definitions {#definitions}
===========

: <dfn>Collection manager</dfn>
:: A person who creates metadata records in a [=collection management system=] and links terms to those records.

: <dfn>Configurator</dfn>
:: A special type of [=collection manager=] who configures the [=collection management system=] for searching the Network of Terms, without requiring vendor modifications.

: <dfn>Collection management system</dfn>
:: A software application for creating, editing, and publishing metadata records that implements the Network of Terms API.

: <dfn>Term</dfn>
:: A concept from a [=terminology source=], identified by a URI, with properties such as prefLabel, altLabel, scopeNote, and broader/narrower relations.

: <dfn>Terminology source</dfn>
:: A source of [=terms=], such as a thesaurus or vocabulary, that is available through the Network of Terms.

: <dfn>Vendor</dfn>
:: An organization that supplies a [=collection management system=].

Requirements {#requirements}
============

These requirements are organized into four phases: selecting sources, searching terms, viewing terms, and publishing links.

Terminology sources {#sources}
--------------------------------

### Search in selected sources ### {#search-sources}

> Searches by [=collection managers=] *MUST* be executed only in selected [=terminology sources=] and *MUST NOT* default to searching all sources.

NDE has observed implementations querying all sources by default. This makes users wait needlessly for slow sources and puts unnecessary load on [=terminology sources=].

### Select sources ### {#select-sources}

> [=Configurators=] *MUST* be able to select which [=terminology sources=] are available for searching in the [=collection management system=] without requiring [=vendor=] involvement.

Allowing customers to make [their own selection](https://termennetwerk.netwerkdigitaalerfgoed.nl/en/sources), 
and being able to adapt it later as need arises, improves the adoption speed of the Network of Terms.

### New sources immediately available ### {#new-sources}

> When new [=terminology sources=] are added to the Network of Terms, they *MUST* become available to [=configurators=] for selection.

Dependence on [=vendors=] to add [=terminology sources=] delays [=collection managers=] from being able to use new sources.

### Identify sources by URI ### {#identify}

> [=Terminology sources=] *MUST* be identified by their dataset URI. Distribution information *MUST NOT* be hardcoded but *MUST* be retrieved dynamically from the Network of Terms.

Distribution information may change over time (e.g. a terminology source’s SPARQL endpoint), but the dataset URI will remain the same.

Search terms {#search-terms}
----------------------------

### Debounce queries ### {#debounce-queries}

> [=Collection management systems=] *MUST* debounce search queries by [=collection managers=].

This prevents excessive requests to [=terminology sources=] while the [=collection manager=] is still typing.

### Minimum query length ### {#min-query-length}

> [=Collection management systems=] *MUST NOT* send queries shorter than 3 characters to the Network of Terms.

Many [=terminology sources=] don’t handle short search strings well.

### Display complete term information ### {#term-info}

> All [information from the Network of Terms](https://docs.nde.nl/services/network-of-terms/graphql/#terms) *MUST* be accessible
in search results without truncation, including prefLabel, altLabel, scopeNote, and broader/narrower terms.

[=Collection managers=] need to see all relevant information about terms to differentiate terms 
and make informed decisions about which terms to link.

### Display source information ### {#source-info}

> For each term, its [source](https://docs.nde.nl/services/network-of-terms/graphql/#source) *MUST* be shown,
including the source’s name and alternateName (short name), and the creator’s name and alternateName.

This helps [=collection managers=] select a term from a source appropriate to the resource and the property they are editing,
for example ‘material’.

### Display error messages ### {#errors}

> [Errors](https://docs.nde.nl/services/network-of-terms/graphql) from the Network of Terms API *MUST* be shown to [=collection managers=].

The Network of Terms queries [=terminology sources=] in real time. Each source returns either a list of [=terms=] or an error.
The API defines two error types:

- **TimeoutError**: the [=terminology source=] did not respond within the [timeout period](https://docs.nde.nl/services/network-of-terms/graphql/#timeouts).
- **ServerError**: the [=terminology source=] responded with an error.

Because errors are reported per source, other sources may still return results successfully.
Displaying these errors communicates to [=collection managers=] that some sources may be [periodically unavailable](https://termennetwerk.netwerkdigitaalerfgoed.nl/en/sources),
through no fault of the Network of Terms.

### Send multilingual queries ### {#multilingual-queries}

> [=Collection management systems=] *MUST* include a [`languages` parameter](https://docs.nde.nl/services/network-of-terms/graphql#multilingual-queries) in queries to the Network of Terms.

Without a language parameter, the Network of Terms returns labels in all available languages combined in a single search result, which is confusing and hard to read.

### Identify client in requests ### {#user-agent}

> [=Collection management systems=] *MUST* send a User-Agent HTTP header identifying the system and its version to the Network of Terms.

This helps NDE to monitor usage and advise vendors in optimizing their implementations.

### Distinguish previously linked terms ### {#distinguish-linked-terms}

> [=Collection management systems=] *MAY* visually distinguish previously linked terms in search results through highlighting or prioritization.

When [=collection managers=] reuse previously linked [=terms=], this improves consistency within the dataset and strengthens interlinking between datasets.

View terms {#view-terms}
------------------------

### Store term URIs ### {#store-term-uris}

> The URI for each linked [=term=] *MUST* be stored in the [=collection management system=].

To maintain stable references to terms, implementations must store the term’s identifier. 
This also enables looking up the term later, to refresh its information in the collection management system.

### Display term information ### {#view-term-info}

> When viewing metadata records in the [=collection management system=],
> all linked term information *MUST* be displayed,
> including [[#term-info|term information]] and [[#source-info|source information]].

This provides context to [=collection managers=] when they are viewing records.

### Cache term information ### {#cache-terms}

> Term information *MAY* be cached but *MUST* then be refreshed from the Network of Terms at a configurable interval.

Caching reduces load on [=terminology sources=]. However, users must be presented with recent term information.

Publish links to terms {#publish-links}
---------------------------------------

### Publish term URIs ### {#publish-term-uris}

> Linked [=term=] URIs *MUST* be included in published datasets.
> The [=term’s=] prefLabel *SHOULD* be included as a literal value alongside the URI.

Consumers of the dataset should have access to linked terms. 
This requirement is in accordance with [[SCHEMA-AP-NDE#reference-terms]].

